narrator's shifting stance in the poem, the unique character of Milton's prelapsarian paradise, and the moral and intellectual status of Adam and Eve before and after the fall. From Satan's arrival in Hell to the expulsion from the garden of Eden, Milton's version of the Genesis myth resonates with the complex thematics of Renaissance colonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aColonies in literature. 0aEpic poetry, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aFall of man in literature. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aPolitical poetry, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172401540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724015423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724015/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles